<p class=3D"p">A variance-covariance matrix is a square matrix that contain=
s the variances and covariances associated with several variables. The diag=
onal elements of the matrix contain the variances of the variables and the =
off-diagonal elements contain the covariances between all possible pairs of=
 variables. </p>=20
<div class=3D"p">For example, you create a variance-covariance matrix for t=
hree variables X, Y, and Z. In the following table, the variances are displ=
ayed in bold along the diagonal; the variance of X, Y, and Z are 2.0, 3.4, =
and 0.82 respectively. The covariance between X and Y is -0.86.=20
<table cellpadding=3D"4" cellspacing=3D"0" summary=3D"" border=3D"0" class=
=3D"simpletable ruled-table"><thead><tr class=3D"sthead">=20
<th style=3D"vertical-align:bottom;text-align:left;" id=3D"d2099123e47" cla=
ss=3D"stentry">&nbsp;</th>
=20
<th style=3D"vertical-align:bottom;text-align:left;" id=3D"d2099123e49" cla=
ss=3D"stentry">X</th>
=20
<th style=3D"vertical-align:bottom;text-align:left;" id=3D"d2099123e52" cla=
ss=3D"stentry">Y</th>
=20
<th style=3D"vertical-align:bottom;text-align:left;" id=3D"d2099123e55" cla=
ss=3D"stentry">Z</th>
</tr>
</thead><tbody><tr class=3D"strow">=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e47" class=3D"stentry"=
>X</td>
=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e49" class=3D"stentry"=
><strong class=3D"ph b">2.0</strong></td>
=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e52" class=3D"stentry"=
>-0.86</td>
=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e55" class=3D"stentry"=
>-0.15</td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"strow">=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e47" class=3D"stentry"=
>Y</td>
=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e49" class=3D"stentry"=
>-0.86</td>
=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e52" class=3D"stentry"=
><strong class=3D"ph b">3.4</strong></td>
=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e55" class=3D"stentry"=
>0.48</td>
</tr>
<tr class=3D"strow">=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e47" class=3D"stentry"=
>Z</td>
=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e49" class=3D"stentry"=
>-0.15</td>
=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e52" class=3D"stentry"=
>0.48</td>
=20
<td style=3D"vertical-align:top;" headers=3D"d2099123e55" class=3D"stentry"=
><strong class=3D"ph b">0.82</strong></td>
</tr>
</tbody></table>
 </div>=20
<p class=3D"p">The variance-covariance matrix is symmetric because the cova=
riance between X and Y is the same as the covariance between Y and X. There=
fore, the covariance for each pair of variables is displayed twice in the m=
atrix: the covariance between the ith and jth variables is displayed at pos=
itions (i, j) and (j, i). </p>=20
<div class=3D"p">Many statistical applications calculate the variance-covar=
iance matrix for the estimators of parameters in a statistical model. It is=
 often used to calculate standard errors of estimators or functions of esti=
mators. For example, logistic regression creates this matrix for the estima=
ted coefficients, letting you view the variances of coefficients and the co=
variances between all possible pairs of coefficients.=20
<div class=3D"alert note"><h6 class=3D"label">Note</h6><p class=3D"notetext=
